### Grid Template

**grid-template** defines the structure of rows, columns, and areas.

---

### Grid Template Columns

```css
.container {
  grid-template-columns: 200px 1fr 200px;
}
```

---

### Grid Template Rows

```css
.container {
  grid-template-rows: 100px 1fr 100px;
}
```

---

### Grid Template Areas

```css
.container {
  grid-template-areas:
    "header header header"
    "sidebar main aside"
    "footer footer footer";
}

.header { grid-area: header; }
.sidebar { grid-area: sidebar; }
.main { grid-area: main; }
.aside { grid-area: aside; }
.footer { grid-area: footer; }
```

Each row in quotes represents one row.
`.` (dot) creates an empty cell.

---

### Grid Template Shorthand

```css
/* grid-template: rows / columns */
.container {
  grid-template: 100px 1fr 100px / 200px 1fr 200px;
}

/* With areas */
.container {
  grid-template:
    "header header header" 100px
    "sidebar main aside" 1fr
    "footer footer footer" 100px
    / 200px 1fr 200px;  /* Column widths */
}
```

---

### The Repeat() Function

```css
grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);          /* 3 equal columns */
grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 100px);        /* 4 fixed columns */
grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr 200px);    /* 1fr, 200px, 1fr, 200px */
```

---

### Autofit with Minmax

```css
.container {
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(300px, 1fr));
}
```

Creates as many 300px columns as fit, then stretches evenly.

---

### Implicit Rows

Rows created by content beyond the template:

```css
.container {
  grid-template-rows: 100px 100px;
  grid-auto-rows: 200px;  /* Extra rows are 200px */
}
```

> **Best Practice:** Use `grid-template-areas` for page layouts - it makes the structure visually clear in CSS.
